    {
      "question": "Show that for any positive integer $n$, the number $n^3 - n$ is always divisible by $6$.",
      "answer": "Since $n^3 - n = (n-1)n(n+1)$, which is the product of three consecutive integers, at least one of which must be a multiple of $2$ and one must be a multiple of $3$. Thus, the product is divisible by $2 \\times 3 = 6$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Factorize the expression $n^3 - n$ as $(n-1)n(n+1)$.",
          "Identify that this is the product of three consecutive integers.",
          "Note that in any three consecutive integers, at least one is divisible by $2$ and exactly one is divisible by $3$.",
          "Conclude that since the product is divisible by both $2$ and $3$, it must be divisible by their product, $6$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$n^3 - n = n(n^2 - 1) = (n-1)n(n+1) \\\\ \\text{Let } P = (n-1)n(n+1) \\\\ \\text{Since } (n-1), n, (n+1) \\text{ are consecutive integers, at least one is even.} \\\\ \\text{Also, one of them must be a multiple of } 3. \\\\ \\text{Therefore, } P \\text{ is divisible by } 2 \\times 3 = 6.$"
      },
