    {
      "question": "Without performing long division, determine whether the rational number $\\frac{147}{120}$ has a terminating or non-terminating repeating decimal expansion. Justify your answer.",
      "answer": "Non-terminating repeating, because the denominator's prime factorization contains a factor other than $2$ or $5$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Simplify the fraction to its lowest terms: $\\frac{147}{120} = \\frac{49}{40}$.",
          "Find the prime factorization of the denominator $40 = 2^3 \\times 5^1$.",
          "Check if the denominator is of the form $2^n \\times 5^m$.",
          "Since $40 = 2^3 \\times 5^1$, the expansion is terminating."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\frac{147}{120} = \\frac{147 \\div 3}{120 \\div 3} = \\frac{49}{40} \\\\ 40 = 2 \\times 2 \\times 2 \\times 5 = 2^3 \\times 5^1 \\\\ \\text{Since the denominator is of the form } 2^n \\times 5^m, \\text{ the decimal expansion terminates.}$"
      },
      "topic": "Real Numbers",
      "subtopic": "Decimal Expansion of Rational Numbers",
